B Bryan meta-analysis code review

K N Thompson, September 2022

In this code review, K N Thompson will replicate all STATA code to conduct the meta-analysis for the publication by B Bryan Bryan, B. T., Andrews, G., Thompson, K. N., Qualter, P., Matthews, T., Arseneault, L. (under review), Loneliness in the workplace: a mixed method systematic review and meta-analysis, Psychological Bulletin.

The stata code used in the paper takes the following steps:

  • Read in data
  • Recode variables
  • Conduct Fishers transformation
  • Prepare data for meta analysis
  • Run meta-analysis
  • Create forest plot

Read in the data

dat.raw <- read_csv("KT_meta_analysis_data.csv")
colnames(dat.raw)

[1] Authors Year N
[4] r Occupational group Loneliness measure [7] Correlate measure Correlate

Recode the variables

STATA code:

* Recode variables
rename var1 authors
label var authors "Study authors"
rename var2 year
label var year "Publication year"
rename var3 n
label var n "Sample size"
rename var4 r 
label var r "Correlation co-efficient"
rename var5 corr_scale
label var corr_scale "Correlate measure"

Below I have renamed the variables to the labels that were set in the STATA code.

co-efficient doesnt need a hyphen.

R code:

dat <- dat.raw %>%
  dplyr::select(
         `Study Authors` = Authors,
         `Publication year` = Year,
         `Sample size` = N,
         `Correlation coefficient` = r, 
         `Occupational group`,
         `Loneliness measure`,
         `Correlate measure`,
         Correlate
  )

colnames(dat)

[1] Study Authors Publication year
[3] Sample size Correlation coefficient [5] Occupational group Loneliness measure
[7] Correlate measure Correlate

Fishers transformation

STATA code:

* Fisher's z transformation
gen z = .5 * ln((1 + r) / (1 - r))
label var z "Fishers z transformation r"
gen sez = sqrt(1/(n - 3))
label var sez "SE of z"

R code:

dat <- dat %>%
  mutate(
    `Fishers z transformation r` = 
      FisherZ(`Correlation coefficient`)
  )

describe(dat$`Fishers z transformation r`)
dat <- dat %>%
  mutate(
    `SE of z` = 
      sqrt(1/(`Sample size` - 3))
  )

describe(dat$`Fishers z transformation r`)

Prepare data for meta analysis

STATA code:

* Meta set data
meta set z sez, studylabel(authors)

I also added in the Correlate and Correlate measure here.

R code:

dat.meta <- dat %>%
  dplyr::select(
         `Study Authors`,
         `Fishers z transformation r`,
         `SE of z`,
         Correlate,
         `Correlate measure`
  )

colnames(dat.meta)

[1] Study Authors Fishers z transformation r [3] SE of z Correlate
[5] Correlate measure

dat.meta <- dat.meta %>%
  mutate(
    Correlate.factor = 
      as_factor(Correlate)
  )
is.factor(dat.meta$Correlate.factor)

[1] TRUE

Run meta-analysis

STATA code:

meta summarize, random(reml) transform(corr) subgroup(corr_scale)

R translation:

  • Restricted Maximum-Likelihood (reml) as the estimator
  • subgroup analysis use the correlate measure? Here we will run a subgroup meta-analysis using Correlate, as well as running separate meta-analyses while stratifying by Correlate.

All studies included together

# all studies
meta_analysis_re_total <- rma(yi = `Fishers z transformation r`,    # effect sizes or outcomes - this is z
                              sei = `SE of z`,                      # standard errors 
                              method = "REML",                      # estimator - random effects specified through REML
                              data = dat.meta                       # dataset
)

# subgroup analysis
meta_analysis_re_sub  <- rma(yi = `Fishers z transformation r`,    # effect sizes or outcomes - this is z
                              sei = `SE of z`,                      # standard errors 
                              method = "REML",                      # estimator - random effects specified through REML
                              mods = ~ Correlate.factor-1,          # create subgroup analysis using the correlates
                              data = dat.meta                       # dataset
)

Seperate meta analyses for each correlate

dat.meta.burnout <- dat.meta %>% filter(Correlate == "Burnout")

Create results table

table <- function(data, model){
  table <- data.frame(matrix(nrow = 1,ncol = 9))
  colnames(table) <- c("Model", "Theta estimate", "Confidence interval lower", "Confidence interval upper", "Standard error", "Q", "tau2", "%I2", "H2") 
  table <- table %>%
    mutate(`Theta estimate` = round(data$b, 3)) %>% 
    mutate(`Confidence interval lower` = round(data$ci.lb, 3)) %>%
    mutate(`Confidence interval upper` = round(data$ci.ub, 3)) %>% 
    mutate(`Standard error` = round(data$se, 3)) %>% 
    mutate(Q = round(data$QE, 3)) %>% 
    mutate(tau2 = round(data$tau2, 3)) %>%
    mutate(`%I2` = round(data$I2, 3)) %>%
    mutate(`H2` = round(data$H2, 3)) %>%
    mutate(Model = c(model))
  return(table)
}
table.burnout <- table(data = meta_analysis_re_burnout, model = "Burnout")
table.job.perf <- table(data = meta_analysis_re_job.perf, model = "Job performance")
table.job.sat <- table(data = meta_analysis_re_job.sat, model = "Job satisfaction")
table.man.rel <- table(data = meta_analysis_re_man.rel, model = "Manager relationship (LMX)")

table.all <- rbind(table.burnout, table.job.perf, table.job.sat, table.man.rel)
table.all
